Panic's Limit
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will face the end, and the usual saying is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Limits to Growth was first published over forty years ago by the Club of Rome, its basic idea has been with us all along.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 Limits to Growth warned humanity that catastrophic collapse is imminent.
But afterwards, we saw financial panics, but no real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius have more than sufficed to meet human consumption.
But the basic idea of The Limits to Growth still holds: we continue a trend of being preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues while neglecting major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book Silent Spring ignited public fear of pollution and also sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 book The Population Bomb said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The purpose of The Limits to Growth was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people are consuming too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a level significantly poorer than today.
This view still resonates today, although it is completely wrong.
For example, the authors of The Limits to Growth predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of their level from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, denture materials, and thermometers, and by the year 2000, mercury consumption had declined by 98%, and prices had dropped by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally predicted to be exhausted by 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, their reserves are higher than in 1970, despite our greatly increased consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and cut prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
The Limits to Growth was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, and there are an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
The rate of malnutrition has been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not defeated us.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where there was no air pollution from suspended particles, and everyone was happy as farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys would make us unable to breathe. Reality is the complete opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people — equivalent to one in every 500 people — died each year from air pollution, most of it from indoor air pollution.
Now, this rate has dropped to one death per 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, the death rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the notion cultivated by The Limits to Growth still influences the thinking of the public and the elites.
Taking recycling, for example, it is usually just a gesture that makes people feel better, costly for the environment and with minimal effect.
For instance, paper is usually sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The processes and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not actually under threat.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation have led to self-destructive policies, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, effective pesticide regulation results in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while pesticide use has created a more affordable and abundant food supply.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — the movement spurred by pesticide panic — would impose an additional $10 billion cost on the United States each year.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland — half the size of modern-day California — would be required.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths per year).
Being obsessed with dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year — equivalent to a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most of them can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of people living in poverty by nearly a billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the publication of The Limits to Growth shows that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring over 100 trillion dollars in benefits by the end of this century, far surpassing the benefits of timid "comfortable" policies driven by fear-mongering.
This requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
